The ruthless Turnus could not be trusted to live in the new era; but oh, the pity of his fall, the pity of his punish- mentl Nowhere more exquisitely does Virgil “stretch out his hands in longing for the further shore,'' nowhere more touchingly express his sense of the incompleteness of the greatest human triumph, than by this last line of the Aeneid, his last word to mankind. His hero has fought, has suffered long, has conquered; yet his conquest itself is cause for sorrow, because it shows that · the deeper enemy, the wiliulness of human passion, has yet to be destroyed.
